      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "fd87552472148630",
      "text": "Certain issues remain critical to understanding the conflict between the farmers and pastoralists. Such issues include the following:"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "bd1a49c2daca19fb",
      "text": "**(a)** Nutritional need for beef meat. Throughout Nigeria and even in West Africa, beef is widely consumed. Indeed, it is the number one meat consumed both by the rich and the poor and one can hardly be tired of it. The implication of this is that it is in high demand and its supply cannot be wished away.  Since the Fulanis are the major rearers and suppliers of cattle we must recognize their importance in the chain of food supply. This is the reality of our situation and any solution to the conflicts between farmers and herdsmen must take cognizance of this fact;"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "5b50d4ac4844c4cc",
      "text": "**(b)** Population factor. As a corollary to the above, the last population census put Nigeria’s population at 140million. This was in 2006 and the population is now projected to have risen to about 170million. Nigeria is a huge market of beef meat and it is expanding. There is no other meaningful source of supply of beef than the cows reared by the Fulanis. It, therefore, amounts to mere wishful thinking to believe that we can somehow get rid of the Fulanis in the supply chain of beef meat in the foreseeable future."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "b57be40e2cb231f3",
      "text": "**(c)**\tImproved health care. This has resulted in an astronomical increase in the population of cattle if compared to what happened some hundred years ago. Furthermore, it is well-known that people (especially Fulanis) hold herds of cattle as a significant store of value and we now have a situation where individuals in the north own them in large numbers. Consequently, demand for grazing has increased substantially. If this is juxtaposed with the problems of climate change, desertification and shrinking forests, one would appreciate the problems faced by pastoralists in their quest for food and water for their animals during the dry season."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "cfd08e84be0c15b7",
      "text": "**(d)**\tThe issue of climate change deserves further elucidation. This problem is a natural phenomenon which has been occurring over time but has escalated in recent times because of the problem of environmental degradation arising from the depletion of the ozone layer due to indiscriminate consumption of fossil fuels. The resultant global warming is exerting pressure on the environment resulting in  desertification and progressive reduction in grazing area which in turn leads to increasing scarcity of green pasture. All these have   escalated conflict between farmers and pastoralists."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "4749fdf25d7913fb",
      "text": "**(e)**\tFarmers’ plight.  The invasion of farms and destruction of crops by Bororo Fulanis have become a serious problem to farmers. They are frustrated and discouraged to the extent that many of them are moving into other occupations. It should be recalled that farming generally is no longer attractive to young people and that elderly peasant farmers constitute the bulk of the farming population."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "3a21f5faf52b7c84",
      "text": "**(f)**\tGovernments’ role. Governments at different levels have not sincerely addressed the conflicts of the farmers and pastoralists. Most of the solutions proffered have been reactive rather than proactive. In the Southern part of the country, for instance, one finds that they are more concerned with punishing erring Fulanis than finding solutions to the problems. This explains why laws are made to punish Fulanis who destroy farms without giving a thought to how to deal with the issue of scarcity of food and water for the cattle which they perennially face. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "5198969b18b9eaf8",
      "text": "What governments seem to be demonstrating is that the Fulanis should move out of their territory to wherever they can graze their cattle even if it means moving from Oyo to Ogun State within the same country. The pastoralists are driven from pillar to post and this probably explains why they, in frustration, sometimes react violently resulting in killing and maiming. It is a sad commentary on the implementation of government policy that the Grazing Reserve Project initiated in 1994 has not been completed. Yet the farmers-pastoralist conflict in intensity shares affinity with the Boko haram insurgency in its devastating effect in Nigeria. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "2f863685779e8d25",
      "text": "**(g)**\tJust as governments do not handle the conflicts between farmers and pastoralists’ proactively, so do the security agencies (which in any case is a constituent of the government) demonstrate lackadaisical attitude to dealing with the conflict. Perhaps, being inadequately equipped to deal with the problem equally hinders their efficiency. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "c8229d4465f36a17",
      "text": "Their usual complaint is that they do not have appropriate logistical support to deal with the problems but it is well-known that they feed fat on the situation.  It is, for instance, alleged that there is hardly any Divisional Police Officer (DPO) posted to Saki who does not end up owning a cattle ranch which he gets mainly from the spoils of the conflict between farmers and pastoralists. The DPOs, therefore, as it were have become “soldiers of fortune.”"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "905dfb2a2768abd9",
      "text": "**(h)** Saki Community’s intervention. The Saki umbrella organization, Saki Parapo and the Saki Chamber of Commerce and Industry have, as earlier stated, often intervened in the conflicts. However, if their intervention is critically examined, it is more about how Saki Cattle Market would be reopened with the aim of reversing the negative economic impact of its closure on the town. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "ba3bedd07e610b28",
      "text": "A careful analysis of the agreement entered into between the community and the cattle breeders association buttresses this point. The agreement which provided that Fulanis should move freely within the area obviously had little or no consideration for the farmers and their crops. It is when the frequency of the conflicts between farmers and pastoralists is assuming greater proportion that Saki Parapo intervenes more actively on behalf of the farmers as its recent action shows.   "
